│ THOUGHT: Now I can see that `getMainOp()` returns the main instruction      │
│ being vectorized. In the `setInsertPointAfterBundle` function, the code     │
│ uses `Front = E->getMainOp()` and `LastInst =                               │
│ &getLastInstructionInBundle(E)`. The issue is that when the bundle contains │
│ both PHI nodes and other instructions, `LastInst` might be a PHI node even  │
│ if `Front` is not.                                                          │
│                                                                             │
│ Looking at the reproducer again, the SLP vectorizer is likely trying to     │
│ vectorize the `%or` and `%or4` instructions, which are not PHI nodes.       │
│ However, `getLastInstructionInBundle` might be returning a PHI node because │
│ of how the bundle is constructed.                                           │
│                                                                             │
│ The fix should be to base the insertion point decision on `Front` (the main │
│ operation) rather than `LastInst`. If `Front` is not a PHI node, then we    │
│ shouldn't treat the bundle as a PHI node bundle, even if `LastInst` happens │
│ to be a PHI node.                                                           │
│                                                                             │
│ Let me implement this fix:                                                  │
│                                                                             │
│ ```bash                                                                     │
│ cd /llvm-autofix-deps/llvm/llvm && sed -i '16030,16037s/bool IsPHI =        │
│ isa<PHINode>(LastInst);/bool IsPHI = isa<PHINode>(Front);/'                 │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                             │
│ ```                                                                         │
